Using the `ptr<>` operator can be a more efficient way to access the pixel values of an image, as it allows you to directly access the memory location of the image data without having to perform any additional indexing or bounds checking.

Here is an example of how you can use the `ptr<>` operator to implement the same functionality as the previous code:


```c
v::Mat r = cv::Mat::zeros(dst.rows, dst.cols, dst.type());

if (ii == 0) {
 for (int i = 0; i < dst.rows; i++) {
 auto dst_row = dst.ptr<uchar>(i);
 auto r_row = r.ptr<uchar>(i);
 for (int j = 1; j < dst.cols; j++) {
 r_row[j - 1] = dst_row[j];
 }
 }
}
else if (ii == 1) {
 for (int i = 1; i < dst.rows; i++) {
 auto dst_row = dst.ptr<uchar>(i);
 auto r_row = r.ptr<uchar>(i-1);
 for (int j = 0; j < dst.cols; j++) {
 r_row[j] = dst_row[j];
 }
 }
}
else if (ii == 2) {
 for (int i = 1; i < dst.rows; i++) {
 auto dst_row = dst.ptr<uchar>(i);
 auto r_row = r.ptr<uchar>(i-1);
 for (int j = 1; j < dst.cols; j++) {
 r_row[j-1] = dst_row[j];
 }
 }
}
else if (ii == 3) {
 for (int i = 1; i < dst.rows; i++) {
 auto dst_row = dst.ptr<uchar>(i);
 auto r_row = r.ptr<uchar>(i-1);
 for (int j = 1; j < dst.cols; j++) {
 r_row[j-1] = dst_row[j];
 }
 }
}
```
The `ptr<>` operator is slightly faster than the OpenCV's built-in functions like `Rect()` and `copyTo()` because it avoids the overhead of creating and managing temporary memory regions and checks for region of interest.

It is worth to note that if your image is large, you should use the `Mat::row` and `Mat::col` functions which are optimized and use the `ptr<>` operator internally instead of a nested for loop.

