To pass data from your React Next.js app into your Bevy Rust game, you can use JavaScript's built-in `postMessage` function to send messages between the two applications.

In your React Next.js app, you can define a function that will send the data to the Bevy Rust game:


```javascript
function sendDataToBevy(data) {
 const iframe = document.getElementById('bevy-game-iframe');
 iframe.contentWindow.postMessage(data, '\*');
}
```
Here, `iframe` is a reference to the `iframe` element that contains your Bevy Rust game, and `data` is the string or API response that you want to send to the game.

In your Bevy Rust game, you can add an event listener to receive the message:


```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use wasm_bindgen::prelude::*;
use wasm_bindgen::JsCast;
use web_sys::{MessageEvent, Window};

#[derive(Default)]
struct GameState {
 // ...
}

#[wasm\_bindgen]
pub fn start\_game() {
 let state = Rc::new(RefCell::new(GameState::default()));

 let window = web_sys::window().unwrap();
 let closure = Closure::wrap(Box::new(move |event: MessageEvent| {
 let data = event.data().as\_string().unwrap();
 // use the data to update the game state
 state.borrow\_mut().update\_game\_state(data);
 }) as Box<dyn FnMut(MessageEvent)>);
 window
 .add\_event\_listener\_with\_callback("message", closure.as\_ref().unchecked\_ref())
 .unwrap();
 closure.forget();

 // ...
}
```
Here, `start_game` is the function that initializes your Bevy Rust game. We create a `Closure` that will be called when a `message` event is received by the window. In the closure, we extract the data from the event, and update the game state using the `update_game_state` method (which you will need to define yourself).

To change a crate resource in the Bevy Rust game, you can use the `Resources` type provided by Bevy. In your `update_game_state` method, you can retrieve the `Resources` object and modify it:


```rust
fn update\_game\_state(&mut self, data: String) {
 let mut resources = Resources::default();
 // add a new string resource using the data from the message
 resources.insert(data);
 // retrieve the resource and use it to change the crate
 if let Ok(s) = resources.get::<String>() {
 self.crate_resource = s.clone();
 }
}
```
Here, `self.crate_resource` is a field in your `GameState` struct that represents the current value of the crate resource. We create a new `Resources` object and insert the data from the message as a new string resource. Then, we retrieve the string resource and use it to update `self.crate_resource`.

Note that this is just an example, and the specific implementation will depend on your game and how you want to update the crate resource.

